  "prompt": "Does the law prohibit money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the law prohibits money laundering in virtually all jurisdictions. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\") by disguising their true source. This is typically done by passing the money through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nLegislative frameworks against money laundering are designed to detect and punish those who attempt to legitimize the proceeds of crime, and to prevent the banking and financial sectors from being used to launder money. In the United States, for example, the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970 requires financial institutions to report certain transactions (such as those over $10,000) to the government, and the USA PATRIOT Act expanded the scope of the BSA's anti-money laundering provisions.\n\nSimilarly, the European Union has several anti-money laundering directives that have been transposed into the national laws of member states. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing, and its recommendations are implemented by its member countries.\n\nMoney laundering is typically treated as a serious criminal offense, and individuals and entities found guilty of money laundering can face substantial fines, imprisonment, and other penalties. Additionally, businesses that fail to implement adequate anti-money laundering controls can be subject to regulatory enforcement actions, including fines, sanctions, and restrictions on their operations.",
